Title: Nicotine Intake in Cigarette Smokers in England: Distribution and Demographic Correlates
AdditionalInformation:
This paper was published in Cancer Epidemiology Biomarkers &  Prevention, a highly rated journal within the specific field.   This study provided the most complete picture yet of the smoke intake of cigarette smokers in England.  It used objective markers of tobacco smoke exposure (salivary cotinine), collected from participants in the Health Survey for England (HSE) 1998 - 2003.  The HSE is a health examination survey of a random sample of the general population living in England; a new sample is selected each year.
We found that cotinine levels increased in smokers with age, peaking around the age of 40y, and were higher in smokers from more disadvantaged groups, which may contribute to their greater risk of developing cancers.
